        <body>
            <entry xml:id="entry_asojnæ" xml:lang="os">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>asojnæ</orth></form>
                <sense xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg><lang/></usg><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>борона деревянная</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>wooden harrow</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Староосетинская форма слова восстанавливается в виде %i*asan%i
                    (ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_k0yroj"/> | %ikurojnæ%i, <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_soj"/> | %isojnæ%i, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æncoj"/> |
                    %iæncojnæ%i, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_moj"/> | %imojnæ%i и т. п.). Эту
                    восстанавливаемую форму нельзя не сблизить с <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>ā̌sā̌n-</w>
                        <gloss><q>камень</q></gloss></mentioned> (борона — ‘подбитое камнями
                    орудие’); хотя такое объяснение не согласуется с современными реалиями (борона
                    %sдеревянная%s), но известно, что названия орудий передаются, как правило, не по
                    материалу или форме, а по выполняемой функции. Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>ās</w>
                        <gloss><q>жорнов</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                            ><w>āsyāne</w>
                        <gloss><q>точило</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Horn._Gr."/><biblScope>7</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>asan-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>ášān</w>
                        <gloss><q>камень</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"
                            ><w>ášani-</w>
                        <gloss><q>наконечник стрелы</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>άκόνη</w>
                        <gloss><q>точило</q></gloss></mentioned>. Стоит отметить, что
                    индоевропейские названия бороны — <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>όξίνη</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/>
                        <w>occa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="goh"><lang/>
                        <w>egida</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="prg"><lang/>
                        <w>aketes</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cel"><lang/>
                        <w>ocet, oged</w></mentioned> — производятся от того же корня %i*aḱ-%i
                    ‘острый’, ‘камень’, с которым мы связываем д. %iasojnæ%i.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">The old Ossetic form is reconstructed as %i*asan%i (cf. <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_k0yroj"/> | %ikurojnæ%i, <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_soj"/> | %isojnæ%i, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æncoj"/> |
                    %iæncojnæ%i, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_moj"/> | %imojnæ%i etc.). This
                    reconstructed form has to be approached to <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>ā̌sā̌n-</w>
                        <gloss><q>stone</q></gloss></mentioned> (harrow is a ‘tool lined with
                    stonesʼ); although such an explanation does not agree with modern realities
                    (harrow is %swooden%s), it is known that tool names are usually inherited not by
                    material or shape, but by the function they perform. Cf. <mentioned
                        xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>ās</w>
                        <gloss><q>millstone</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                            ><w>āsyāne</w>
                        <gloss><q>grindstone</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Horn._Gr."/><biblScope>7</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>asan-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>ášān</w>
                        <gloss><q>stone</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"
                            ><w>ášani-</w>
                        <gloss><q>arrow head</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>άκόνη</w>
                        <gloss><q>grindstone</q></gloss></mentioned>. It is noteworthy that the
                    Indo-European names for the harrow, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>όξίνη</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/>
                        <w>occa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="goh"><lang/>
                        <w>egida</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="prg"><lang/>
                        <w>aketes</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cel"><lang/>
                        <w>ocet, oged</w></mentioned> are derived from the same root %i*aḱ-%i
                    ‘sharp’, ‘stone’, with which we associate Digor %iasojnæ%i.</etym>
            </entry>
